By 2 September 1991, Clarence Thomas was ready to appear, as a
Republican nominee, before the Senate committee for confirming him as
a Supreme Court justice. The conversion of Thomas from liberal
Democrat and Malcolm X admirer to conservative Republican took place
over a period of several years beginning with his law school training
at Yale in 1971-1974.

Thomas' philosophy became one of taking advantage of the opportunities
afforded by the U.S. and that to rely on government for hand-outs was
nothing less than slavery. He opposed preferences given to racial
minorities who suffered discrimination and called for a colorblind
Constitution.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d13"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="SJMN91-06184021"
SELECTOR="C"
SUMMARIZER="E">         

Clarence Thomas, the Supreme Court justice, attributes his values to
his grandparents who raised him in his early years.  They, more than
anyone else, shaped his beliefs on self-reliance, individualism, and
determination to survive under segregation.

Thomas was born of poor parents in 1948 in Pinpoint, Georgia.  He
attended religious schools for a time.  He left after discovering that
they were not a haven from segregation.

Thomas' real interest was the law.  He graduated from Yale Law in
1974.  He was selected for the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in 1990.

Thomas lives with his wife and son in Virginia.</SUM>

<SUM
