On July 1, 1991 President Bush nominated Clarence Thomas, a black
conservative republican, to replace Thurgood Marshall on the Supreme
Court.

Thomas is a bootstrap conservative who does not believe in affirmative
action, quotas or racial preferences for minority groups, saying that
these are unconstitutional.

Thomas studied for the priesthood at one time.  He has never taken a
stand on abortion, which Catholicism opposes.  Abortion rights
proponents intend to oppose him.  His stand on the major issues is
largely unknown.  President Bush believes that Thomas is a self- made
success.

If confirmed, he could be on the Supreme Court by October, 1991.</SUM>

