On September 11, 1991, as Clarence Thomas waits for his U.S.  Supreme
Court Justice confirmation, the media was focusing on his wife,
Virginia.  The question foremost in their minds was, how much
influence will she have on Clarence Thomas' decisions if he is
confirmed?

Some see her as more than a dutiful wife.  She has lobbied against
comparable-worth legislation.  Religious rights groups are concerned
by her anti-cult activities.  Other critics believe that since his
wife is white, Thomas has rejected his black roots and lacks a sense
of community.  Both Thomases believe that women and minorities are
harmed by affirmative action.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d13"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="SJMN91-06290146"
SELECTOR="C"
SUMMARIZER="E">         

Pinpoint, Georgia, the home town of Clarence Thomas, made no secret of
its pride in its favorite son.  Its citizens, including his mother,
Leola Williams, were anxiously awaiting the results of the U.S. Senate
vote on 16 October 1991 for U.S. Supreme Court justice.

When the confirmation came, it brought joyful and prayerful
exclamations from his mother and the townspeople.

A reporter asked about the sexual harrassment charge brought against
her son by Anita Hill in 1981-1983. His mother responded with a prayer
and the comment that Hill was "put up to it" by someone else.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d13"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ910709-0115"
SELECTOR="C"
SUMMARIZER="E">         

With Clarence Thomas about to go for confirmation as a Supreme Court
justice, there are conclusions to be drawn.

The author, Peggy Noonan, believes that Thomas "made it" because he
was loved by his mother, by his grandparents, and by the nuns who
taught him.

Thomas, says Noonan, did notq make it on his own but has been 
helped all his life by affirmative action.  

Noonan believes that because people helped Thomas, it shows that real
change in a democracy comes from the people up, not from the
government down. She thinks that the choice of Thomas is the peoples'
will.</SUM>
